<subSubSection id="D984653DFFCDFFB0F4CBFBBE4693CEC8" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFCDFFB0F4CBFBBE4693CEC8" blockId="47.[151,1437,1150,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F4CBFBBE457ACE80" bold="true" box="[151,286,1150,1175]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name “ 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F658FBBE465DCE80" box="[516,569,1150,1175]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">leios</emphasis>
” is Greek for “smooth” which alludes to the bald, smooth abactinal and marginal surfaces. “ 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F52BFB6445D5CEAC" box="[375,433,1188,1211]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">astra</emphasis>
” is the female form for “star.” The species epithet “ 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F7A4FB62401ACEAC" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[1016,1150,1186,1211]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F7A4FB62401ACEAC" box="[1016,1150,1186,1211]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” for triangle refers to the distinctive triangular shape of the arms in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D984653DFFCDFFB0F49BFB2A451CCF78" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFCDFFB0F49BFB2A451CCF78" blockId="47.[151,1437,1150,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F49BFB2A4525CF14" bold="true" box="[199,321,1258,1283]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Abactinal and marginal plates smooth with no granules. No crystalline granules on plates. Marginal plates eight per interradius (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFCDFFB0F58AFACE4653CF30" box="[470,567,1294,1319]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig.18A</figureCitation>
), large and wide, forming distinct border, approximately 47% of total radius (r) on disk. Superomarginal plates abutted along arm radius along full arm distance. Actinal plates covered by granules (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFCDFFB0F559FA96450FCF78" box="[261,363,1366,1391]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D984653DFFCDFFB0F49BFABA40ADCFA0" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFCDFFB0F49BFABA40ADCFA0" blockId="47.[151,1437,1150,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F49BFABA452BCF84" bold="true" box="[199,335,1402,1427]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Comments.</emphasis>
Based on a comparison with concepts of similar goniasterids, character evidence does not support placement of this species within a known genus; a new genus and species therefore is proposed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D984653DFFCDFFAFF49BFA04449CCAEF" lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFCDFFB0F49BFA0445FFCCEC" blockId="47.[151,1437,1150,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F49BFA0445A0CFCC" authority="Mah, 2018" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,452,1474,1499]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F49BFA0445A0CFCC" box="[199,452,1474,1499]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8D957DFFFCDFFB0F593FA024676CFCC" box="[463,530,1474,1499]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F593FA024676CFCC" bold="true" box="[463,530,1474,1499]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
possesses smooth abactinal and marginal plate surfaces which are devoid of granules, although smaller ones are present around the periphery. These characters are also observed in several other goniasterids, including 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F5B9F9CC469FCC34" box="[485,763,1546,1571]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F5B9F9CC4693CC34" authority=", Glyphodiscus" authorityName="Glyphodiscus" box="[485,759,1546,1571]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Iconaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Iconaster, Glyphodiscus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F76BF9CA405ACC34" authority="(Mah 2005)" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Mah" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[823,1086,1546,1571]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Lithosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F76BF9CA47C9CC34" box="[823,941,1546,1571]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Lithosoma</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F50F4B47FFCDFFB0F7E2F9CA4052CC34" author="Mah, C. L." box="[958,1078,1546,1571]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" refId="ref72029" refString="Mah, C. L. (2005) Cladistic Analysis of the Goniasteridae (Asteroidea: Falvatoidea): Phylogeny, Evolution and Biodiversity. Unpublished PhD Dissertation, University of Illinois, Illinois, 378 pp." type="book" year="2005">Mah 2005</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
that differ in that their actinal plate surfaces are devoid of granules and other accessories, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F7B1F9EF408FCC50" authority="Mah, 2018" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[1005,1259,1582,1607]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F7B1F9EF408FCC50" box="[1005,1259,1582,1607]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F0ABF9EE41F8CC50" bold="true" box="[1271,1436,1582,1607]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8D957DFFFCDFFB0F0ABF9EE412FCC50" box="[1271,1355,1582,1607]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
n. sp.
</emphasis>
granules are present. 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F5D6F9944650CC7C" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1911" box="[394,564,1620,1643]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pontioceramus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F5D6F9944650CC7C" box="[394,564,1620,1643]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Pontioceramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F631F9924693CC7C" authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[621,759,1618,1643]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Diplasiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F631F9924693CC7C" box="[621,759,1618,1643]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Diplasiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share similarities with 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F058F99440CDCC7C" authority="Mah, 2018" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[1028,1193,1618,1643]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F058F99440CDCC7C" box="[1028,1193,1618,1643]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">L. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F0EDF992412ECC7C" bold="true" box="[1201,1354,1618,1643]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8D957DFFFCDFFB0F0EDF9924165CC7C" box="[1201,1281,1618,1643]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
n. sp.
</emphasis>
in that they possess smooth, bare abactinal and marginal plate surfaces, in conjunction with granules covering the actinal surface; however, there are significant differences in overall R/r, body, arm, and plate shape. 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F0EEF95A414BCCA4" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[1202,1327,1690,1715]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F0EEF95A414BCCA4" box="[1202,1327,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in that it possesses fine, crystalline bosses on the abactinal plate surfaces, granules on the marginal plates, and exhibits a different R/r.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="912136B6FFCDFFB0F49BF8C645D9CDC5" blockId="47.[151,1437,1150,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F49BF8C646DBCD08" authority="McKnight 1973" authorityName="McKnight" authorityYear="1973" box="[199,703,1798,1823]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Lithosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="novaezelandiae">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F49BF8C6459CCD08" box="[199,504,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Lithosoma novaezelandiae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="F50F4B47FFCDFFB0F659F8C646DBCD08" author="McKnight, D. G." box="[517,703,1798,1823]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="171 - 195" refId="ref72961" refString="McKnight, D. G. (1973) Additions to the asteroid fauna of New Zealand: family Goniasteridae. New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Records, 1 (13), 171 - 195." type="journal article" year="1973">McKnight 1973</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, as outlined in 
<bibRefCitation id="F50F4B47FFCDFFB0F7DCF8C640DCCD08" author="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G." box="[896,1208,1798,1823]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 270" refId="ref69285" refString="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G. (2001) The Marine Fauna of New Zealand: Echinodermata: Asteroidea (sea-stars), Order Valvatida. NIWA Biodiversity Memoir, 117, 1 - 270." type="journal article" year="2001">Clark and McKnight 2001</bibRefCitation>
bears a superficial resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F50BF8EC463CCD54" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[343,600,1834,1859]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F50BF8EC463CCD54" box="[343,600,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F634F8EA4771CD54" bold="true" box="[616,789,1834,1859]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">n. gen, n. sp.</emphasis>
in terms of abactinal and marginal plate shape and morphology. However, 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F5FCF88F46FCCD70" authority="Mah, 2018" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[416,664,1870,1895]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F5FCF88F46FCCD70" box="[416,664,1870,1895]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F6C3F88E4750CD70" bold="true" box="[671,820,1870,1895]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8D957DFFFCDFFB0F6C3F88E468ACD70" box="[671,750,1870,1895]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
n. sp.
</emphasis>
differs in that crystalline bosses such as are present on the abactinal plates of are absent. 
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFCDFFB0F664F8B44751CD9C" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[568,821,1906,1931]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F664F8B44751CD9C" box="[568,821,1906,1931]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFCDFFB0F71CF8B24786CD9C" bold="true" box="[832,994,1906,1931]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">n. gen, n. sp.</emphasis>
also possesses granular covering and distinct subambulacral spination on the actinal and adambulacral surface, respectively, both characters absent from 
