<subSubSection id="D984653DFFD2FFADF49BF9394537C92F" lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD2FFAFF49BF93947ADCDAE" blockId="48.[151,1437,1785,1977]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Abactinal surface planar, abactinal plate region pentagonal and sits below the plane of the superomarginals. Plates hexagonal to irregularly polygonal (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD2FFAFF6DBF8DA4694CD24" box="[647,752,1818,1843]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
). Plate surfaces bare and smooth, granules absent. Surface opaque, crystalline inset granules not observed. Plates larger proximally becoming smaller distally adjacent to contact with superomarginal plate boundary. Individual plate boundaries distinct. Individual plates bearing 25–30 small, round granules with approximately five to seven per side. Primary circlet distinct, with seven carinals present from disk to arm. Madreporite triangular, flanked by three plates.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C5E1663EFFD3FFAEF4CBF85844D9CDFC" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" startId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" targetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" targetPageId="49">
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD3FFAEF4CBF85844D9CDFC" blockId="49.[151,1437,1944,2027]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF4CBF8584544CDB9" bold="true" box="[151,288,1944,1966]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">FIGURE 18.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="569E4D35FFD3FFAEF574F859466DCDB9" authority="Mah, 2018" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2018" box="[296,521,1944,1966]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Leioastra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="triangularis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF574F859466DCDB9" box="[296,521,1944,1966]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Leioastra triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8D957DFFFD3FFAEF64DF858462FCDB9" box="[529,587,1944,1966]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF64DF858462FCDB9" bold="true" box="[529,587,1944,1966]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF05EF858407FCDB9" bold="true" box="[1026,1051,1944,1966]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">A.</emphasis>
Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF4CBF87644CACDDB" bold="true" box="[151,174,1974,1996]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">B.</emphasis>
Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF635F87646E5CDDB" bold="true" box="[617,641,1974,1996]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">C.</emphasis>
Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. 
<emphasis id="A3EAEAA4FFD3FFAEF7B4F8764065CDDB" bold="true" box="[1000,1025,1974,1996]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">D.</emphasis>
Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD0FFADF49BFF5745A7CBBA" blockId="50.[151,1436,151,896]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Marginal plates large, swollen, strongly convex in outline. Superomarginal and inferomarginal plates ten in each series (arm tip to arm tip) (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF5A7FF7C4607CAC3" box="[507,611,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18A</figureCitation>
). Superomarginals and inferomarginal plates correspond 1:1 but are offset creating a angular contact at edges. Marginal plates smooth bare, granules absent from surfaces of both superomarginals and inferomarginals (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF614FEC446CBCB0B" box="[584,687,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
). Plates with ~25–30 tiny granules per edge forming a distinct but very thin boundary around each plate. Superomarginal plates abutted over midline, three to four. Distal superomarginals becoming more triangular in shape (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF6A6FE8C47E2CB73" box="[762,902,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18A, B</figureCitation>
). Proximal superomarginal and inferomarginal plates more trapezoid in outline. Pre-terminal superomarginals sometimes very small, indistinct. Terminal triangular, smooth surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD0FFADF49BFE774562C82A" blockId="50.[151,1436,151,896]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Actinal surface composed of approximately three series of plates (one series, adjacent to inferomarginal contact is incomplete) (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF5FBFE1C4675CBE3" box="[423,529,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). Individual plates quadrate, angular to irregularly quadrate in outline. Actinal plates covered by 40–60 evenly spaced granules, with approximately seven to ten forming peripheral border on each side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD0FFADF49BFD8846DDC8DA" blockId="50.[151,1436,151,896]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Furrow spines five to six, short blunt. Subambulacrals three, half as long with further series behind them becoming more consistent with granular morphology on actinal surfaces (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF7B9FDAC402BC893" box="[997,1103,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18D</figureCitation>
). Each oral plate bisected by distinct furrow flanked on either side by four to five paired series of granules (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF052FD4F4012C8BF" box="[1038,1142,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). Oral plate furrow spines five to six, with one spine projecting into mouth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="912136B6FFD0FFADF49BFD184537C92F" blockId="50.[151,1436,151,896]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Two marginal plates present interradially show damage with distinct chunks absent from the distal edge (
<figureCitation id="09A52A33FFD0FFADF133FD174489C903" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,235,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[151,1436,235,1870]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leioastra triangularis n. sp. Holotype IE-2007-3946. r=1.9, r=1.0 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. B. Closeup of arm and superomarginal plates. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Closeup of furrow region. Scale bar=0.5 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615962/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 18A, C</figureCitation>
). It is unclear if this was caused during collection or perhaps from natural causes, such as predation (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="F50F4B47FFD0FFADF4CBFCE0452CC92F" author="Neumann, C." box="[151,328,800,824]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="65 - 70" refId="ref73317" refString="Neumann, C. (2000) Evidence of predation on Cretaceous sea stars from north? west Germany. Lethaia, 33 (2), 65 - 70. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00241160050150177" type="journal article" year="2000">Neumann 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
